The year is coming to a close and I’ve been reflecting on a lot of things this year 🌿

This year hasn’t been what I thought it was going to be — there have been a lot of unexpected ups and downs, and a hell of a lot of growth points. I feel like I notice my growth when I notice growth on my plants — and maybe that’s a weird way of looking at the world, but when I look at my plants, I’m reminded of the different paces we take in life, and how even the toughest environments can produce growth. 

The rubber tree in this photo is a good example of that: I swear this plant is constantly riddled with something — most recently thrips 😅 and before that, plenty of spidermites. But through it all, she still has so much new growth, and the leaves on this plant are so much bigger and stronger than before. 

I think that’s how life works, too. Through all the good and the bad, we often come out stronger and better than before 💚

Near the end of last year, I started opening up more about my journey with #longcovid and found so many people in my community were dealing with it, too. Long covid is complicated, and oftentimes misunderstood, but I want this to be a safe space where people can talk about what’s been going on, the symptoms they experience, and everything in between. 

While there are many physical symptoms that come with long covid, there are also a handful of mental ones that are seldom talked about. 

For me, my anxiety and depression have increased exponentially. I’ve been dealing with depression and anxiety for years and years, but long covid has definitely had a heavy impact. Another symptom that comes with this is brain fog 😶‍🌫️ 

Brain fog is one of those things that’s really hard to explain unless you’ve experienced it. It’s similar to the feeling of going to a room to find something, and upon entering, you immediately forget what you were going in there for — but all the time. I’ve double sent emails, I ask questions about things I really should already know…and sometimes that gets hard! 

That being said, this journey has taught me the importance of self-care and self-compassion. I’ve been making the time to look after me — whether this be settling down with a book, running a bath after a long day, or chasing sunsets. I’ve also found comfort in the healing power of plants — they bring a sense of comfort and serenity to my space. As I continue to navigate this new normal, I remind myself to take it one day at a time and to find ways to take care of my mental and physical well-being. 

If you’re in a similar boat and navigating this new normal, I’d love to chat so feel free to comment down below or pop into my DMs if that’s more comfortable. We’re in this together 🤝🏻🫶🏻

it’s #longcovidawarenessmonth and I’m excited for a number of reasons, most particularly to spread more awareness and help others garner a better understanding of this chronic illness 🫶🏻

Long covid is more than just a temporary illness. It’s a chronic condition that can have lasting effects your health and well being. It can be debilitating and, for many, finding support and care can be tough. It’s not yet fully understood, making it all the more important to continue researching and raising awareness about this condition. 

Here are some ways to get involved:

💙 follow profiles and pages that advocate for people with long covid such as @longcovidsos @longcovid @longcovidjustice @dysautonomiaintl @longcovidalliance 

💙 take time to research and learn about the condition and how it can impact people both physically and mentally

💙 spread the word about long covid and it’s impact on people’s lives by sharing information on social media, talking to friends and family, and by engaging in discussions with your community

💙 continue to encourage vaccinations

💙 help advocate for policy changes that support people with long covid and other chronic illnesses, such as increased access to healthcare, disability benefits, and workplace accommodations 

💙 help fund research if you’re able: I’ve linked @dysautonomiaintl ‘s Long Covid Research Fund in my bio if you’re interested in helping fund research studies to help identify the causes of long covid, identify effective treatments, and more

happy wednesday 💚 my ficus elastica ruby has been thriving recently, and I had to show off this gorgeous new leaf growing in the center. 

I’ve had this plant since August and it’s grown a ton, especially for this PNW climate! Here’s how I care for it:

💚 lots of light — I keep all my plants in south facing windows to get the best light possible, even in the darker months

💚 frequent pest checks — I’ve had numerous run-ins with spidermites on these plants, so I’m careful to check the leaves during waterings

💚 I water this about every two weeks, which is just enough time for the soil to completely dry out. These plants can be susceptible to root rot in my experience, so I try to be extra careful to not overwater

💚 I like to wipe down the leaves on most watering days for this plant as it gathers a fair amount of dust 

💚 finally, I fertilize this once a month and it seems to love that!

So today, I’m posting something simple — me and two of my favorite ficus elasticas, two plants that I find hardy and fairly easy to care for, which is great on heavier days. I particularly love my ficus elastica ruby— the tricolored leaves bring a bright pop of color to any environment 🪴

Anyway. This is your reminder to take it easy. Let your creative energy flow when you can, but also give yourself space to take a step back when necessary 🌷

Let’s propagate my snake plant (again!)

A few years ago, I propagated another snake plant, unsuccessfully and posted it on TikTok and Reels. The video went viral and even with time, not only did the cutting not root, but I was met with the unkind side of the internet. This time around, I’m here to show that you CAN propagate snake plants the way I show here and showed in my original video. 

Here’s how I did it:

✂️ grab a clean pair of scissors or shears 

🌱 cut off the snake plant leaf that you want to propagate — you can cut this straight across or create triangle shaped cuts for more space for rooting

💧 then I place the snake plant cutting into water, with the freshly cut portion facing down in the water 

⏰ then I waited! It took about 2-3 weeks for roots to start showing

Have you tried this out before? 🫶🏻

preparing my plants for colder weather! ❄️ 

as the weather gets colder, it’s important to check in on our plants and make some changes to keep them happy. here’s how I prep for fall/winter:

🌿 pest control — I always check for pests, specifically spidermites for me, and take preventative action by wiping down my leaves with neem oil 

🌿 move plants away from drafty windows and colder areas in your space

🌿 wipe down your leaves so your plants can soak in as much light as possible

🌿 continue to fertilize if you want to keep seeing growth! plants still need food in the winter months. I like to use @growarber when I fertilize my plants

🌿 decrease waterings as needed — I find my plants need a lot less water during the colder and darker seasons

🌿 I like to use supplemental light to help my plants continue to grow throughout the winter and to make up for the darker weather 

🌿 finally, it’s okay if you have some dead and dying leaves here and there. just like the trees outside, our plants lose their older leaves as the seasons change 🍃 

if you found this helpful, like and share this with a friend! 💚🌿

Do you have hydrophobic soil? 

Hydrophobic soil is soil that repels water instead of absorbing it due to a waxy residue that builds up on the surface. You may notice this when you see water resting on top of the soil, slowly draining, or when you see the soil compacting. 

Here are a few ways you can deal with hydrophobic soil:

🪴 repot the plant into some better soil — usually my go to solution, but if you don’t have the time you can also do the following:

🪴 aerate the soil — using something like a chopstick or a straw, poke holes gently around the soil, being sure not to hit any roots too hard. this should loosen up some of the soil and allow for better drainage

🪴 bottom watering! place your plant in a container, fill it up with water and wait for a while as your plant soaks up as much of the water it needs. I bottom water a lot of my plants in general and find this can be a really efficient way to avoid overwatering plants, too.

I picked this monstera adonsonii back in April this year from a big box store, where it was waterlogged, leaves were tangled within themselves, and it was sitting in a corner of the store with little light. 🌱 I water when the soil is completely dry. With this plant being so, so waterlogged before, I’m extra careful with this plant, just because I want her to thrive. So I wait till the soil is completely dry. 

🌱 I fertilize with every other watering to keep those leaves coming in 

🌱 this plant doesn’t get as much light as it could — it sits fairly far away from the window, but it seems to be doing alright where it is, so I’m not moving it for the time being 🤷🏼‍♀️ 

there’s something about the feeling of reviving a plant, or at least helping it get back on its feet, so to speak 💚

Another update on my snake plant propagation from a little while back! 🌿

Here’s how I did it:

✂️ grab a clean pair of scissors or shears 

🌱 cut off the snake plant leaf that you want to propagate — you can cut this straight across or create triangle shaped cuts for more space for rooting

💧 then I place the snake plant cutting into water, with the freshly cut portion facing down in the water 

⏰ then I waited! It took about 2-3 weeks for roots to start showing, and a few months to see some pups 

Have you tried this out before? 🫶🏻

it’s always a little frustrating when a so-called easy plant starts dying on you 😅 I’ve had this beautiful zz plant for a few years now, and kept it in the same spot — only this year she decided she’s unhappy. I’ll likely repot her in some new soil soon and check out the roots, but for now I’m propagating a few more pieces. Here’s what I’m doing:

🌿 take a clean pair of scissors or shears and clip a zz leaf right at the base

🌿 you can let it callus up overnight or just go ahead and put it straight into your growing medium — whether that’s water, soil, etc. I’m using water to try and propagate mine. 

there are a couple ways to propagate this plant — and all of them require lots of patience, so we’ll wait and see what happens!! 🌿
